<frame name="FR_Attributing_cause" ID="10005" xsi:schemaLocation="../schema/frame.xsd" xmlns="http://framenet.icsi.berkeley.edu" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" domains="Cognitive_positions,Verbal_communication,Causality">
    <definition>&lt;def-root&gt;An &lt;fen&gt;Attributor&lt;/fen&gt; either explains a &lt;fen&gt;Known_state_of_affairs&lt;/fen&gt; by providing a &lt;fen&gt;Cause&lt;/fen&gt; or presents a &lt;fen&gt;Responsible_party&lt;/fen&gt; as being responsible for the &lt;fen&gt;Known_state_of_affairs&lt;/fen&gt;. The latter possibility is only possible for some of the LUs of this frame (all except "expliquer"). This may be done verbally, or it may be part of the &lt;fen&gt;Attributor&lt;/fen&gt;'s internal world view.  

&lt;ex&gt;&lt;/ex&gt;
Distinctions with other frames:
&lt;ex&gt;≠ &lt;frframe&gt;Explaining_the_facts&lt;/frframe&gt;: in the latter, the LUs present the Cause as an explanation for the State_of_affairs, without any local realization of the Attributor. &lt;/ex&gt;
&lt;ex&gt;≠ &lt;frframe&gt;FR_Justifying&lt;/frframe&gt;: In FR_Attributing_cause, the Attributor supplies what they present as a CAUSE for a Known_state_of_affair whereas in FR_Justifying, what the Communicator states is a reason for viewing the State_of_affair or Act they might be responsible for as LEGITIMATE.&lt;/ex&gt;

&lt;ex&gt;&lt;/ex&gt;
&lt;asf&gt;Relation to fndata-1.5&lt;/asf&gt; New in ASFALDA.
&lt;/def-root&gt;</definition>
